<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 2:9<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2561f160630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>2.</label.designator><headtext>Witnesses</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I257d4190630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.designator>B.</label.designator><headtext>Competency</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05c2682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>2:9.</label.designator><headtext>Children</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Children of 14 years of age and older are presumed to be competent to testify; however there is no presumption that a child younger than that is incompetent to testify. <eos/><bos/>The case law in this area is dependent on case-specific facts. <eos/><bos/>For example, children as young as five years of age have been found competent[<footnote.reference refid="Ic1785a807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] and incompetent.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic17881907fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Historically, the court sought to ascertain whether a young witness understood the nature of an oath. <eos/><bos/>However, this requirement has been abandoned as a test because oaths are connected <page no="13"/>to religious belief.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic17881917fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] It is necessary for a child to understand the difference between telling the truth and telling an untruth.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic17881927fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018082" w-serial-number="1990142453" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id1fd22127fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Hall v. State</ital></cite.query>, the Georgia Court of Appeals found a child abuse victim competent when she testified that she knew it was bad to tell a lie despite her inability to explain the difference between the truth and a lie.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic178a8a07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] In cases involving deprivation as defined by <cite.query w-src-number="0287018082" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST15-11-2" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id1fde5607fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 15-11-2</cite.query> or crimes in which the child is a victim or a witness to a crime, the child shall be considered competent to testify. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018082" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST49-5-183.1" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id1fde5617fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 49-5-183.1(i)</cite.query> provides for testimony by children under the age of 14 at hearings held pursuant to an abuse investigator&apos;s report.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic1785a807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018082" w-serial-number="1983102018" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id1fad8227fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Mackler v. State, 164 Ga. App. 874, 298 S.E.2d 589 (1982)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic17881907fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018082" w-serial-number="1983217174" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id1fb4d527fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Strickland v. State, 250 Ga. 827, 301 S.E.2d 891 (1983)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="13"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic17881917fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018082" w-serial-number="1963126418" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id1fbc2827fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Jones v. State, 219 Ga. 245, 132 S.E.2d 648 (1963)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic17881927fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018082" w-serial-number="1979106170" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id1fc5ec27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Bradley v. State, 148 Ga. App. 722, 252 S.E.2d 648 (1979)</cite.query>, a seven-year-old was found competent after stating, <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“My mother said if I always tell the truth and didn&apos;t lie, I would get some money after we finished court.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic178a8a07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018082" w-serial-number="1990142453" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id1fd70327fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Hall v. State, 196 Ga. App. 523, 396 S.E.2d 271 (1990)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 2:9<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
